               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18360509-1339-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1339-18360509 t18360509-1339-offence-1 t18360509-1339-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18360509-1339-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-1339-18360509 t18360509-1339-offence-1 t18360509-1339-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1339. <persName id="def1-1339-18360509" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1339-18360509" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1339-18360509" type="surname" value="BARREGAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1339-18360509" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JAMES BARREGAN</hi>
                  </persName> and <persName id="def2-1339-18360509" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-1339-18360509" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1339-18360509" type="surname" value="RILEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1339-18360509" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">SAMUEL RILEY</hi>
                  </persName> were indicted for<rs id="t18360509-1339-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18360509-1339-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18360509-1339-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="pocketpicking"></interp> stealing, on the <rs id="t18360509-cd-184" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360509-1339-offence-1 t18360509-cd-184"></join>8th of April</rs>, 1 necklace, value 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18360509-name-1273" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1273" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1273" type="surname" value="TANSLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1273" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360509-1339-offence-1 t18360509-name-1273"></join>Charles Tansley</persName>, from the person of <persName id="t18360509-name-1274" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1274" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1274" type="age" value="4"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1274" type="surname" value="TANSLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1274" type="given" value="AMELIA"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360509-1339-offence-1 t18360509-name-1274"></join>Amelia Tansley</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1275" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1275" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1275" type="surname" value="MARYBANK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1275" type="given" value="JAMES HENRY"></interp>JAMES HENRY MARYBANK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a shoemaker, and live in Church-street, Deptford. On Friday, the 8th of April, about five minutes after five o'clock in the afternoon, I was looking out of my shop window, and saw the two prisoners standing on the opposite side of the way, looking down at Miss Tansley—Barregan took the neckalce from the child's neck—the other prisoner stood by, looking out, about a yard and a half from Berre<lb></lb>gan—he stood still for a moment, and Barregan ran away—Riley ran away soon afterwards—he appeared to be looking at Barregan while he took the necklace—they were looking each other is the face—the little girl was</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183605090223"></xptr>
               <p>between them—the child ran home and called Mrs. Tansley—she came out, and I told her of it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Why did you not follow them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I had slippers on, and overall trowsers, and no coat, handkerchief, or hat—there was nobody passing by—I did not call out—the glass of my window was down—I saw them distinctly—I did not know them before—I went in pursuit, at last, and found the prisoners, and a third person—they were secured, but no necklace was found on them—when I saw them first, they stood opposite my window, looking at the girl—they walked a little further on them, and one stood on the curb-stone, and the other against the house—the little girl looked up at Riley, and Barregan put his hands and took the necklace off—I saw them searched about half an hour after the Becklace was taken—I remember a man calling on me soon after, about this business—I told him Mrs. Tansley did not wish to prosecut<lb></lb>or, and I did not wish to go forward as evidence.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you say you could do something for him unless you were moved? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I swear that—I said I though the man was at the office on the Satur<lb></lb>day—I might have said I knew what he had come about, and would not an<lb></lb>swer him any questions, as he had been talking to me about the matter be<lb></lb>fore—I though he came to me to know the particulars, and I told him he knew the particulars, as I thought he was at the office on Saturday, and he said he was not—he did not use the word. "compromise"—I told him he wished he had not come to me, for then he would have seen we did not wish to prosecute—because Barregan's sister came with the man, crying, but we were compelled to come, and I must state the truth.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1276" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1276" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1276" type="surname" value="TANSLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1276" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN TANSLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Charles Tansley, and live in Church-street, Deptford. My daughter Amelia, had a coral necklace on, worth 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—she is about four years old, or rather more—she had no recol<lb></lb>lection of the prisoners.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1277" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1277" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1277" type="surname" value="MURRAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1277" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES MURRAY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable R</hi> 151.) On Friday afternoon, the 8th of April, about half-past five o'clock, the prisoners were given in charge to me, by Maybank, in Church-street—there was a young man in their com<lb></lb>pany, and when I took hold of the prisoners, he went away, and took no notice of me—I called him back, and he came back—I found no necklace.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1278" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1278" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1278" type="surname" value="RUSSELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1278" type="given" value="JERRSMIAH"></interp>JERRSMIAH RUSSELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am shopman to Mr. Moore, a grocer, No.31, Pitfield-street, Hoxton. I was in company with the prisoners on Friday in Easter-week—I have known them from their infancy—I started from London with them, with the intention of seeing a friend at Greenwich—I was walking three or four yards from them—I remember their being taken into custody, and I went to the station-house with them—they did not attempt to take any necklace at all—I was not taken into custody—I was searched at the station-house because I was with them—they could not have taken a necklace from any body without my seeing them.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183605090224"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What time did you leave London to go to Deptford? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About three o'clock, as near as I can recollect—we were on the right-hand side of the archway—they were apprehended at the end of Church-street about a quarter of a mile from Maybank's. and about twenty minutes after five o'clock—it was ten minutes after five o'clock when we were on the rail-road, when we gave our tickets up—we did not go within 100 yards of Maybank's shop—we did not stop any where—we walked on the right-hand side of the rail-road, and Maybank's is one the left-hand, through the archway—the prisoners were taken on the right-hand side of Church-street—one part of the railway goes very close to Maybank's house—we came on the railway to go to see Jones, at Greenwich college—we never went under the archway—we could not be near Maybank's—we were at the corner of Church-street, in the Broadway—I came from Holborn—one of the prisoner is a shoemaker, and comes from Saffron-hill, and the other is a printer, and comes from very close to the spot—we had a holiday that day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1279" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1279" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1279" type="surname" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1279" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN THOMAS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a boot and shoe maker, and live in Peter-street, Clerkenwell. On Friday in Easter week I happened to go down to Dock<lb></lb>head, and at the top of Church-street I saw two boys looking at a bill—it was near about five o'clock—I saw a little child—one of the boys was con<lb></lb>siderably taller than the other—I saw the tall one snatch something from the child's neck, which I considered was a necklace, and run away with it, and the other soon followed—it was near the station-house—I did not follow them, being lame from an accident I have received—I afterwards heard of two boys being taken up for this robbery, and came to Newgate to identify them—I saw the prisoners—they are not the boys who committed the theft.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How came you to Newgate? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Because I saw this robbery committed, and not being able to follow them, I went to several streets, thinking to see them, to have them taken, but I could not, and returned home—I did not know Barregan before this transaction—I first saw him in Newgate—I did not know Riley before—I do not know whether either of them live in Clerkenwell—I never heard it—I went to Deptford by the rail-way that day—I got there about half-past four o'clock—I got into Church-street just before five o'clock, as near as I can guess—I had no watch with me—I was never in Deptford before, and walked into Church-street just for a ramble round the place—I did not tell any of the shopkeeper in the street what I had seen—I should know the persons again who took the necklace—they went under the arch-way towards the rail road—they went down Church-street in front of me—I gave no alarm—there was no one by at the time—I went to Newgate of my own accord, to give evidence against them if they were the right people—the prisoners did not ask me to go.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How did you know the prisoners were in Newgate? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I was in company, and said I saw this robbery committed, and one of my acquaint<lb></lb>ancee, named Phillips, who lives at Chelsea, said, "There are two taken up for the robbery, by the name of Barregan and Riley, and committed to Newgatee"—I put down the names, and went to Newgate and saw the prison<lb></lb>ers, and to my surprise found they were not the two who committed the robbery—I had not seen the two who committed the robbery before—they had not come down by the rail-road with me—one of the parties had a drab coat on, and the other a corduroy jacket—the tall one was nearly five feet seven inches—I cannot say how tail the short one was—I did not notice what coloured neckcloth the tall one had on.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How came you here as a witness, how did you know the trail was coming on? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I found the father of Riley out after I saw them in New<lb></lb>gate, in Saffron-street—I do not know the witness Russell—I have known him since the 24th of April—on the Sunday I called on Riley—I did not go there with him—I never saw Russel at Riley's—I have only seen him in Court, Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday—I never saw him before Monday—I was never at his house, nor he at mine—I never met him at any place—I found out Riley's father by his son's directions.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1280" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1280" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1280" type="surname" value="BEADLE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1280" type="given" value="WILLAIMS"></interp>WILLAIMS BEADLE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a fur-skin dresser, and live at No. 4 Saffron-street,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183605090225"></xptr>
               <p>about one hundred yards from Barregan—I have known him about three years—I went to Maybank's house to speak to him—Riley's father gave me his direction—he told me he did not wish to come forward unless he was required—he said he wanted nothing to say to me, that he had seen me before—I had not been to the office, and when he found out his mistake, he related the circumstances of the case to me—he said he saw one of the prisoners take the necklace, and he was sorry for it—I said I knew them to be respectable—he said, "I have lived in Deptford five years, and have my living to get, and if I do anything wrong, I must leave, Deptford altogether"—I do not know Thomas, or where he lives.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360509-name-1281" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1281" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1281" type="surname" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-name-1281" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN THOMAS</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined. Q.</hi> How did you get admission to New-gate? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> By passing as the father of Riley—I found I must pass as some relation in order to see them—I passed at the gate as Riley's father—I tried to get in as his uncle, and they would not let me in; and I tried as no relation at all, and they would not lot me in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">J.H. MAYBANK</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined. Q.</hi> Describe exactly the direction the two persons, you saw took from your shop? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They went up Church-street, towards the Broadway—that would lead through the archway—the rail-road crosses Church-street—it was in Broadway I gave them in charge—they must have passed under the archway to get to where I saw them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long was it before you got out and followed them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About a quarter of an hour—there was no difficulty in going the dis<lb></lb>tance in that time—I went twice that distance—I saw them distinctly run to the archway—Barregan ran straight on, and Riley stood at the corner of the arch, and looked back—I have no doubt of them whatever—they were taken, about a quarter of a mile from the archway—there was no man standing in the street at the time the robbery was committed—I have heard Thomas's evidence—there was no man standing near the spot.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> There could be no man on your side of the street without your seeing him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not at the distance I could see—I opened my door directly after, and there was nobody—the train of carriages comes down every half-hour I believe—it does not pass my door—I lost sight of the prisoners for about a quarter of an hour—I live about a mile and a quarter from Greenwich Hospital.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you see the prisoners take the necklace from the child's neck? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I could not go out in my overalls.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18360509-1339-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18360509-1339-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360509-1339-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value=""></interp>NOT GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Before Mr. Sergeant Arabin</hi>.</p>
            </div1>
